Africa
[1] Cholera - Nigeria
Date: Thu 23 Jun 2022
Source: Punch Nigeria [edited]
https://punchng.com/ncdc-records-74-cholera-deaths-2339-suspected-cases/


NCDC records 74 cholera deaths, 2339 suspected cases
----------------------------------------------------
The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control said no fewer than 74 persons have been reportedly killed by cholera in 30 states in 2022. The latest cholera situation report by the NCDC also showed that there are a total of 2339 suspected cases of the infection as of 29 May 2022. The agency noted that of the suspected cases since the beginning of 2022, the age group 5 years is the most affected age group for males and females. It also said, of all suspected cases, 50% are males, and 50% are females.

The agency said 5 states -- Taraba (651 cases), Cross River (593 cases), Katsina (134 cases), Kano (124 cases) and Benue (100 cases) account for 68% of all cumulative cases, while 6 LGAs across 2 states --Cross River (3) and Taraba (3) reported more than 100 cases each in 2022. It added that 30 states have reported suspected cholera cases in 2022. These are Abia, Adamawa, Akwa Ibom, Anambra, Bauchi, Bayelsa, Benue, Borno, Cross River, Delta, Ekiti, Gombe, Imo, Kaduna, Kano, Katsina, Kebbi, Kogi, Kwara, Lagos, Nasarawa, Niger, Ondo, Osun, Oyo, Plateau, Rivers, Sokoto, Taraba and Zamfara.

In the reporting month of May 2022, 8 states reported 137 suspected cases -- Anambra (2), Gombe (1), Imo (3), Kaduna (4), Kano (68), Niger (1), Plateau (22) and Taraba (36). There was a 60% decrease in the number of new suspected cases in May Epi week 18-21 (137) compared with April Epi week 13-17 (342).

In Nigeria, cholera is an endemic and seasonal disease, occurring annually mostly during the rainy season and more often in areas with poor sanitation, with the 1st series of cholera outbreaks reported between 1970 and 1990, the agency noted.

[Byline: Lara Adejoro]

