Asia
[3] Cholera - Nepal (Kathmandu)
Date: Tue 21 Jun 2022
Source: Dr Sher Bahadur Pun [edited]
<drsherbdr@yahoo.com>


Nepal reported the 1st 2 (18- and 23-year-old females) laboratory-confirmed (stool culture) cases of _V. cholerae_ in residents of Kathmandu, who were admitted on 16 Jun 2022 to Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital. _Vibrio cholerae_ O1 Ogawa serotype has been isolated in an 18-year-old female patient. This isolate showed sensitivity to ampicillin, tetracycline and chloramphenicol. Both patients were members of the same family. Patients are undergoing treatment at this hospital. More probable (RDTs positive) cases are being admitted to this hospital, meaning more cases of _V. cholerae_ are expected in the capital, Kathmandu in the days to come.

--
Communicated by:
Dr. Sher Bahadur Pun
Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital, Kathmandu, Nepal
<drsherbdr@yahoo.com>

[ProMED thanks Dr. Pun for this report. As a review, the flagellar (H) antigens of _Vibrio cholerae_ are shared with many water vibrios and, therefore, are of no use in distinguishing strains causing epidemic cholera. The O (somatic) antigens, however, do distinguish strains of _V. cholerae_ into 139 known serogroups. Almost all of these strains of _V. cholerae_ are nonvirulent. Until the emergence of the Bengal (O139) strain (which is "non-O1"), a single serogroup, designated O1, has been responsible for epidemic cholera.

There are 3 distinct O1 serotypes, named Ogawa, Inaba, and Hikojima, each of which may display the "classical" or El Tor phenotype (or biotype). The biotypes are distinguished by their expression of surface antigens A, B, and C. Ogawa contains antigens A and B; Inaba antigens A and C; and Hikojima antigens A, B, and C. The latter serotype is relatively rare. - Mod.LL]

